"The sea is ours": Bolivia, blockaded, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Marines patrol an armored boat in the naval headquarters of La Paz.
Public buildings have a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motto: "The sea returns to us by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout blockaded Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the nineteenth century is still present. Just as the desire to sail on the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, Bolivia awaiting a decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of the Bolivian request. Bolivia wants that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile be required to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about Monday’s decision.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and stipulated that it would not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice rendered its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even hurt him.
“The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ bellicose rhetoric undermined all the remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that it will be very complicated to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - who remains to this day one of Latin America's most popular presidents - was using the maritime problem as a political crutch.
