North Korea says disarmament will “in no case” be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that the continued sanctions strengthened his mistrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the World Atomic Energy Organization’s annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho said last year that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures”, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known criticism of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps gradually, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected demands to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and accentuates the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even opposing "the declaration of an end to war".
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us plead do not know us.
The problem is that maintaining the sanctions increases our suspicion.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the U.S. leader earlier this week.
Instead, he highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the denuclearization side was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Still, Ri’s tone of speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened the United Nations last year to “totally destroy” North Korea, has been praising the courage with which Kim has applied disarmament measures this year, but added that much remains to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang saying progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced his “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night.
A professor has noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of themselves
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student came up to me and said, “Why am I only being told this in my senior year?”
She said no one had ever talked to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
First taught this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of health services at the university, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bed.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not instantly change the behavior of students.
However, in our opinion, they have a right to know this information – in the same way that you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in “having a night off” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that this course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar program of study before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students predict an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up times, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
