Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now, a page of our Sunday Morning Almanac: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and the Counter Turns... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as seen in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is this?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger meter, it's used to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
“Through these headphones, we can actually hear the effects of the atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “Say, it sure jumps out there!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
