Germany's new warship still postponed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace aging Cold War warships, but it won’t be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman, the commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the all-new frigates of Baden-Württemberg, was postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but the worrying issues that arose after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the newest frigates for up to two years outside the home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the relentless delays mean that the forward-thinking warships – which should allow Germany to project its force overseas – will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed frigate F125 made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but German media reported a number of "software and hardware flaws" that rendered the warship useless in the event of deployment on combat missions.
Software deficiencies were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships would be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which is half the crews of the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which decreases its efficiency and reduces the ability of the Navy to make future improvements.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is estimated to weigh twice as much as ships of a similar class used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the failures of the computer system, the price of the project as a whole - including the training of the crew - is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), compared to 2.2 billion initially.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval force is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament’s defence committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is in fact “short of ships able to deploy.”
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were downgraded but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
Researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will follow bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional analysis of the sound will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their territorial behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as prairie creation and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affect perches and result in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as pet cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight path.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
David Thompson, manager of the domain, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a great place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
It emphasizes the importance of verifying the presence of bats before proceeding to the maintenance of the properties, because unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, it can thus cause the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
