Red Tide Info Point: Decreasing concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which raises concerns about declining concentrations.
The Red Tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from north of Pinellas to south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations on the Sarasota County floor or offshore, medium concentrations in Charlotte County or offshore, high concentrations in Charlotte County or offshore, and low concentrations in the broader Collier County and offshore.
Respiratory irritation persists in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in Northwest Florida during the past week.
